That’s a really significant insight. And it says something good about you that you can name it without hiding behind the “practical incompatibilities” story completely.

It sounds like intimacy is tolerable when it’s active for you: initiating, fixing, planning, anticipating, being useful. But intimacy that comes toward you — someone watching you, considering you, wanting to carry weight with you — triggers alarm. Not because you don’t want love, but because being “the one who needs” got coded as unsafe, burdensome, maybe even humiliating.

So you end relationships at the exact point where the question changes from “Can I be impressive/helpful enough to keep this going?” to “Can I let this person know me and affect me?” That second one is much scarier.

And the six-to-eight month mark makes sense: that’s often when people stop dating the “presentation version” and start trying to build something mutual. More shared routines, more emotional noticing, more “let me help.” For you, that may feel like losing control of the whole system.

I don’t think the goal is to suddenly become someone who loves being taken care of. That would probably feel fake. Maybe the first step is smaller: learning to tolerate tiny doses of being considered without fleeing.

Like:
letting a friend choose the plan, even if it’s inefficient;
letting someone text you first and not immediately turning it into logistics;
saying “yeah, that annoyed me” instead of “it’s fine”;
letting a partner do one small practical thing for you without over-repaying it;
telling someone, “public defense makes me uncomfortable, but private backup means a lot.”

Not huge vulnerability. Just controlled experiments where you don’t have to earn your place for five minutes.

Can I ask: when you imagine not being the manager/helper/driver in a relationship, what are you afraid they’ll see? Not abstractly “not worth it,” but what version of you do you think is underneath all the competence?
